        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"total_weeks\":16,\"goal_description\":\"Return From Injury — Plantar Fasciitis Recovery & Base Rebuild\",\"phases\":[{\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":10,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":14,\"intensity_distribution\":\"100% easy (run/walk as needed)\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"notes\":\"The entire focus here is tissue tolerance, not fitness. Your foot is healing, and the goal is to accumulate time on feet at easy effort without provoking symptoms. All runs stay at 5:58/km or slower — the slow end of your easy range — with walking breaks introduced any time you feel foot discomfort. Three days per week maximum, with Saturday as your longest run. Weekly distance increases no more than 10% per week. A deload week occurs in week 4, dropping back to week 1 volume. If foot pain returns or worsens at any point, reduce to walk-only and contact your physiotherapist before continuing.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":13,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":18,\"intensity_distribution\":\"95% easy / 5% moderate (no speed work)\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":351,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":344,\"notes\":\"With four weeks of symptom-free running behind you, this phase gently extends run duration toward and occasionally beyond 20 minutes — but only with physiotherapist clearance to do so. Cross-training (cycling, swimming, pool running) can supplement on non-run days to build aerobic capacity without foot loading. Easy pace shifts slightly toward the middle of your range (5:44–5:58/km) as your body adapts. A deload week in week 8 consolidates the gains. Walking breaks remain available any time — using them is smart, not a setback.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Build\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":18,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":25,\"intensity_distribution\":\"85% easy / 15% moderate (tempo only if cleared for speed work)\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"LongRun\",\"Tempo\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":344,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":329,\"notes\":\"This phase marks the transition from injury recovery to genuine base building. Long runs on Saturday begin to feel like real long runs again, building toward 60–75 minutes at easy effort. Tempo work (at 4:29/km threshold pace) is introduced only if your physiotherapist has cleared you for speed work by this point — if not, all runs remain easy and the volume progression still applies. The 10% weekly cap remains firm. Deload in week 12. This is where your pre-injury fitness starts to come back online, and consistency here matters more than any single workout.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Peak\",\"weeks\":2,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":25,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":28,\"intensity_distribution\":\"80% easy / 20% hard\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"LongRun\",\"Tempo\",\"Interval\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":336,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":312,\"notes\":\"Two weeks of peak training to consolidate your rebuilt base. Easy pace moves toward the faster end of your range (5:24–5:36/km), reflecting improved fitness. Interval work at 4:12/km is introduced only if you are fully cleared and symptom-free. Long runs reach their maximum duration for this plan. This is not a peak in the traditional race-prep sense — it is the ceiling of your return-to-training arc, demonstrating that you have rebuilt a solid, injury-resilient foundation.\",\"includes_deload\":false},{\"phase_type\":\"Recovery\",\"weeks\":2,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":18,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":15,\"intensity_distribution\":\"100% easy\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"notes\":\"A planned recovery block to close the 16-week plan. Volume drops back to early-plan levels, all intensity is removed, and the focus is on consolidating adaptation and giving your foot a final opportunity to fully settle. This is not the end of your running — it is the launchpad for your next training cycle, which can target a return to racing. Use these two weeks to reflect on what worked, what your foot is telling you, and what goal feels right for the next chapter.\",\"includes_deload\":false}],\"rationale\":\"James, here is how I thought about building this plan for you. You have a genuine pre-injury VDOT of 46.5 — that fitness is not gone, it is waiting. But right now, your right foot is the limiting factor, not your cardiovascular system or your experience. So this plan is structured around one core principle: earn the right to train harder by proving the foot can handle more. The 16-week arc moves through two Base phases, a Build, a short Peak, and a Recovery block. The first eight weeks are almost entirely about tissue tolerance — keeping you moving, keeping the foot happy, and rebuilding the habit of consistent training without provoking a setback. Pace is held at the slow end of your easy range (5:58/km) throughout the early phases because easy really does mean easy, and because your current fitness is likely below your pre-injury VDOT 46.5 after the layoff. The 10% weekly volume cap is non-negotiable here — plantar fasciitis is notoriously sensitive to load spikes, and the most common mistake in PF recovery is doing too much too soon when it starts feeling better. Deload weeks every 3–4 weeks are built in as a structural feature, not an afterthought. Speed work is gated behind physiotherapist clearance — your physio has cleared you for easy running only, and that boundary is respected throughout the plan. Tempo and interval work appear in later phases as options, but only if clearance is granted. The three-days-per-week structure is honoured throughout, with Saturday anchored as your long run day. Cross-training is offered in the middle phases as a way to build aerobic capacity on non-run days without adding foot load. This plan is designed to get you back to consistent, pain-free running and set you up for a return-to-racing cycle — likely a 10K build — in the second half of 2026.\",\"warnings\":\"Important things to keep in mind before you start. First, this plan is built on your physiotherapist's clearance for 20-minute easy runs only — any progression beyond that requires updated clearance from your physio. If foot pain returns or changes character at any point, stop running and consult your physiotherapist before continuing. Do not redistribute missed mileage to other days — if you miss a run, simply move on to the next scheduled session. Speed work (tempo, intervals, repetitions) must not begin until you have explicit clearance from your physiotherapist, regardless of where you are in the plan. Walking breaks are a legitimate and encouraged tool throughout — using them when your foot speaks up is the smart move, not a failure. Finally, plantar fasciitis recovery is non-linear. Some days will feel better than others, and a flare-up does not mean you are back to square one. Stay in close contact with your physiotherapist throughout this plan.\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
